[[Image:London Air Ambulance G-EHMS (1).jpg|thumb|right|The [[London Air Ambulance]] in action]]
'''Emergency medical services in the United Kingdom''' provide immediate care to people with acute illness or injury, and are predominantly provided by the four [[publicly funded health care]] systems: the [[National Health Service]] (for England), [[Health and Social Care in Northern Ireland]], [[NHS Scotland]] and [[NHS Wales]].{{Citation needed|date=April 2009}} Emergency calls should be made via [[999 (emergency telephone number)|999]] or [[112 (emergency telephone number)|112]].

==Role of the ambulance services==
[[Image:Motorcycle paramedic London Ambulance Service.jpg|thumb|right|A paramedic's motorcycle in Birmingham]]
Public ambulance services across the UK are required by law to respond to four types of requests for care,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nhsdirect.nhs.uk/articles/article.aspx?articleId=529&sectionId=21958|title=Ambulance Service Definition|accessdate=2007-06-15}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> which are:
* Emergency calls (via the [[999 (emergency telephone number)|999]] or [[112 (emergency telephone number)|112]] system)
* Doctor's urgent admission requests
* High dependency and urgent inter-hospital transfers
* Major incidents

Ambulance trusts and services may also undertake non-urgent patient transport services on a commercial arrangement with their local hospital trusts or health boards, or in some cases on directly funded government contracts.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nhs.uk/England/AuthoritiesTrusts/Ambulance/Default.aspx|title=NHS Ambulance Trusts Description|accessdate=2007-06-15}}</ref> This is an area where an increasing amount of private firms are taking business away from the trusts.

Emergency ambulance work in all NHS bodies and most voluntary and private firms is based on the guidance published by the [[Joint Royal Colleges Ambulance Liaison Committee]] (JRCALC).{{Citation needed|date=February 2009}}

==Public ambulance services==
===England===
[[Image:Nhs amb crest.gif|left|80px|thumb|Device of [[National Health Service (England)|NHS]] ambulance services in England and Wales]]
{{see also|Pre 2006 NHS ambulance services}}
Emergency medical services are provided through local [[ambulance]] services, known in England and Wales as trusts. Each service in England is specific to a one or more local authority areas, and so the country is divided across a number of ambulance services, in a similar way to the [[Law enforcement in the United Kingdom|police]].

In England there are twelve ambulance 'trusts', with boundaries generally following those of the regional government offices.<ref name=NHS1>{{cite web|url=http://www.nhsdirect.nhs.uk/articles/article.aspx?articleId=529|title=NHS Information on Ambulance Services|accessdate=2007-06-14 |archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20070611151034/http://www.nhsdirect.nhs.uk/articles/article.aspx?articleId=529 <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 2007-06-11}}</ref>

