===Scotland===
[[File:Ambulancelogo.jpg|left|80px|thumb|Device of the [[Scottish Ambulance Service]]]]
[[Image:Ambulances.jpg|right|thumb|Two [[Mercedes-Benz Sprinter|Mercedes Sprinter]] vehicles of the [[Scottish Ambulance Service]]]]
<!-- [[Image:SN54 FFW Scottish Ambulance Service.jpg|thumb|right|SN54 FFW is a Land Rover Freelander that is used as a rapid response vehicle as part of the Scottish Ambulance Service. The light bar is attached to the roof rails which means fewer holes in the roof. This not only makes the fitting easier, but also increases the re-sale value of the car when it is sold to the public after being retired.]] -->

The [[Scottish Ambulance Service]] is a Special Health Board funded directly by the Health Department of the [[Scottish Government]].<ref name=scot>{{cite web|url=http://www.scottishambulance.com/index.asp|title=Scottish Ambulance Service Website|accessdate=2007-06-15 |archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20070604011115/http://www.scottishambulance.com/index.asp <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 2007-06-04}}</ref> Until 1974, ambulance cover in Scotland was originally provided by a combination of the [[British Red Cross]] and [[St Andrews Ambulance]].<ref name=saa>{{cite web|publisher=St Andrews First Aid|title=St. Andrew's  Ambulance - Our History|url=http://www.standrewsambulance.org.uk/history.htm|accessdate=2009-08-05}}</ref> In financial year 2008â€“2009, the service employed 3,797 staff across five divisions and attended to 599,052 accident and emergency incidents.

Complementing and working alongside the Scottish Ambulance Service is the [[Emergency Medical Retrieval Service]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.emrs.scot.nhs.uk/|title=Emergency Medical Retreival service|month=June | year=2010|accessdate=2010-06-12|publisher=EMRS}}</ref>  This unique medical initiative is based at [[Glasgow City Heliport]] and, staffed by [[consultant]]s, uses various road and air assets to provide patients in remote and rural areas with rapid access to the skills of a consultant in emergency or intensive care medicine as well as facilitating transfers to larger, better equipped city hospitals. The team respond to calls 24 hours a day, utilising road vehicles, helicopters and fixed-wing aircraft.

Scotland has Britain's only publicly funded [[Air Ambulance]] service, consisting of two [[Eurocopter EC 135]] Helicopters (based in [[Glasgow]] & [[Inverness]]) and two [[Beechcraft Super King Air|Beechcraft B200C King Air]] fixed-wing aircraft (based at Glasgow & [[Aberdeen]]). In 2008/09, the Air Ambulance Division flew 3,797 air ambulance missions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scottishambulance.com/what_we_offer/air_wing.asp|title=Scottish Ambulance Service Air Wing|accessdate=2007-06-15}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> 

